UCPR r 36.16(3A) and (3B)
 permits the court, within 14 days after the judgment or order is entered, to make an order to set aside or vary the entered judgment or order, as if it had not been entered: see Capital Finance Australia Ltd v Chief Executive Officer of Customs [2007] NSWSC 1368;  BC200710326  (order entered the previous day, words inadvertently omitted, orders revoked and replaced with orders with the missing words inserted — change alternatively made pursuant to 
r 36.17
). The power is subject only to the limitations that the general law imposed on the variation of judgments and orders prior to entry (see 
[36.16.45]
) and it is not confined to the variation of ancillary orders: Rockcote Enterprises Pty Ltd v FS Architects Pty Ltd (No 2) [2008] NSWCA 205;  BC200807789 at [10] , [11] and [59].

Liberty to apply is implied in relation to ancillary matters, even in the case of final orders: Fritz v Hobson (1880) 14 Ch D 542  (application for costs of an interlocutory motion after final judgement where costs had been reserved and not dealt with in the judgment). It may also be implied from the nature of the order (even though it is not ordinarily implied in the case of final orders that fully dispose of the proceedings: Re McPherson; Willan v Union Trustee Co of Australia Ltd [1909] VLR 103 ) where the order is one which requires, or may require, further directions of the court in order to be carried into effect: Cristel v Cristel [1951] 2 KB 725. For example, it may be that with a declaratory order there is an implied liberty to apply at least where it is made against a public authority (cf Supreme Court Act 1970 
s 65
): Royal Insurance Co Ltd v Mylius (1926) 38 CLR 477 at 497; 32 ALR 446 ; Mudge v A-G (Vic) [1960] VR 43 at 54–5 .

to extend time, notwithstanding the expiry of the time for extension set out in 
s 459R
 of the Corporations Act 2001 (Cth): (Elyard Corp Pty Ltd v DDB Needham Sydney Pty Ltd (1995) 61 FCR 385; 133 ALR 206;  BC9501558 );
